<div class="container-fluid py-4">
  <div class="row">
    <div class="col-lg-3">
      <!-- Sticky Table of Contents -->
      <div class="card sticky-top" style="top: 1rem;">
        <div class="card-header bg-primary text-white">
          <h6 class="mb-0"><i class="bi bi-list-ul"></i> Table of Contents</h6>
        </div>
        <div class="card-body p-0">
          <nav class="nav flex-column">
            <a class="nav-link" href="#introduction">Introduction</a>
            <a class="nav-link" href="#step1">1. Understanding Tests</a>
            <a class="nav-link" href="#step2">2. Creating Your First Test</a>
            <a class="nav-link" href="#step3">3. Choosing Evaluators</a>
            <a class="nav-link" href="#step4">4. Configuring Evaluators</a>
            <a class="nav-link" href="#step5">5. Creating Test Data (Datasets)</a>
            <a class="nav-link" href="#step6">6. Generating Data with AI</a>
            <a class="nav-link" href="#step7">7. Running Tests</a>
            <a class="nav-link" href="#step8">8. Analyzing Test Results</a>
            <a class="nav-link" href="#step9">9. Managing Tests</a>
            <a class="nav-link" href="#step10">10. Best Practices</a>
            <a class="nav-link" href="#common-issues">Common Issues</a>
            <a class="nav-link" href="#next-steps">Next Steps</a>
          </nav>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="col-lg-9">
      <!-- Header -->
      <div class="mb-4">
        <h1 class="display-5"><i class="bi bi-clipboard-check"></i> Testing Guide</h1>
        <p class="lead text-muted">
          Learn how to create comprehensive tests for your AI agents to ensure quality and reliability.
        </p>
      </div>

      <!-- Introduction -->
      <section id="introduction" class="mb-5">
        <div class="card border-primary">
          <div class="card-header bg-primary text-white">
            <h4 class="mb-0"><i class="bi bi-info-circle"></i> What is Testing in PromptTracker?</h4>
          </div>
          <div class="card-body">
            <p>
              Testing in PromptTracker allows you to validate your AI agents <strong>before deploying them to production</strong>.
              Tests help you ensure your agents behave correctly across different scenarios, maintain quality standards,
              and catch regressions when you make changes.
            </p>

            <div class="alert alert-info mb-3">
              <strong><i class="bi bi-lightbulb"></i> Key Concept:</strong> Tests vs Monitoring
              <ul class="mb-0 mt-2">
                <li><strong>Tests</strong>: Pre-deployment validation with controlled test data</li>
                <li><strong>Monitoring</strong>: Post-deployment evaluation of real production calls</li>
              </ul>
            </div>

            <h5 class="mt-4">What You'll Learn</h5>
            <ul>
              <li>How to create tests with automated evaluators</li>
              <li>How to build datasets for comprehensive testing</li>
              <li>How to use AI to generate test scenarios</li>
              <li>How to run tests and interpret results</li>
              <li>Best practices for maintaining test quality</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- Step 1: Understanding Tests -->
      <section id="step1" class="mb-5">
        <div class="card">
          <div class="card-header bg-light">
            <h3 class="mb-0">Step 1: Understanding Tests</h3>
          </div>
          <div class="card-body">
            <p>A <strong>Test</strong> in PromptTracker consists of three main components:</p>

            <div class="row g-3 mb-4">
              <div class="col-md-4">
                <div class="card h-100 border-primary">
                  <div class="card-body">
                    <h5 class="card-title"><i class="bi bi-card-checklist text-primary"></i> Test Definition</h5>
                    <p class="card-text small">
                      Basic information: name, description, and whether the test is enabled.
                    </p>
                  </div>
                </div>
              </div>
              <div class="col-md-4">
                <div class="card h-100 border-success">
                  <div class="card-body">
                    <h5 class="card-title"><i class="bi bi-check-circle text-success"></i> Evaluators</h5>
                    <p class="card-text small">
                      Automated checks that determine if the agent's response passes or fails.
                    </p>
                  </div>
                </div>
              </div>
              <div class="col-md-4">
                <div class="card h-100 border-info">
                  <div class="card-body">
                    <h5 class="card-title"><i class="bi bi-database text-info"></i> Test Data</h5>
                    <p class="card-text small">
                      Input variables (datasets) used to run the test across multiple scenarios.
                    </p>
                  </div>
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>

            <h5>Test Execution Flow</h5>
            <div class="bg-light p-3 rounded">
              <ol class="mb-0">
                <li><strong>Input:</strong> Test data (variables) is provided to the agent</li>
                <li><strong>Execution:</strong> The agent processes the input and generates a response</li>
                <li><strong>Evaluation:</strong> Evaluators check the response against defined criteria</li>
                <li><strong>Result:</strong> Test passes if all evaluators pass, fails otherwise</li>
              </ol>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- Step 2: Creating Your First Test -->
      <section id="step2" class="mb-5">
        <div class="card">
          <div class="card-header bg-light">
            <h3 class="mb-0">Step 2: Creating Your First Test</h3>
          </div>
          <div class="card-body">
            <h5>Where to Create Tests</h5>
            <p>Tests are created from the <strong>Testing</strong> section of a Prompt Version or Assistant:</p>

            <div class="alert alert-primary">
              <strong><i class="bi bi-arrow-right-circle"></i> Navigation:</strong>
              <ol class="mb-0 mt-2">
                <li>Go to <strong>Testing Dashboard</strong></li>
                <li>Click on a Prompt or Assistant</li>
                <li>Click on a specific version</li>
                <li>Scroll to the <strong>Tests</strong> section</li>
                <li>Click <strong>"+ New Test"</strong> button</li>
              </ol>
            </div>

            <h5 class="mt-4">Basic Test Information</h5>
            <p>When creating a test, you'll need to provide:</p>

            <table class="table table-bordered">
              <thead>
                <tr>
                  <th>Field</th>
                  <th>Description</th>
                  <th>Example</th>
                </tr>
              </thead>
              <tbody>
                <tr>
                  <td><strong>Name</strong></td>
                  <td>A unique identifier for the test</td>
                  <td><code>greeting_premium_customers</code></td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                  <td><strong>Description</strong></td>
                  <td>What the test validates</td>
                  <td>"Ensures greeting is personalized for premium customers"</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                  <td><strong>Enabled</strong></td>
                  <td>Whether the test is active</td>
                  <td>✓ Checked (enabled by default)</td>
                </tr>
              </tbody>
            </table>

            <div class="alert alert-success">
              <strong><i class="bi bi-check-circle"></i> Pro Tip:</strong>
              Use descriptive names that clearly indicate what the test validates. This makes it easier to
              understand test failures and maintain your test suite.
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- Step 3: Choosing Evaluators -->
      <section id="step3" class="mb-5">
        <div class="card">
          <div class="card-header bg-light">
            <h3 class="mb-0">Step 3: Choosing Evaluators</h3>
          </div>
          <div class="card-body">
            <p>
              <strong>Evaluators</strong> are automated checks that determine if a response passes or fails.
              You can add multiple evaluators to a single test - the test passes only if <em>all</em> evaluators pass.
            </p>

            <h5>Available Evaluators</h5>
            <p>PromptTracker provides several built-in evaluators:</p>

            <div class="accordion" id="evaluatorsAccordion">
              <!-- Content Quality Evaluators -->
              <div class="accordion-item">
                <h2 class="accordion-header">
                  <button class="accordion-button" type="button" data-bs-toggle="collapse" data-bs-target="#contentEvaluators">
                    <i class="bi bi-file-text text-primary"></i>&nbsp; Content Quality Evaluators
                  </button>
                </h2>
                <div id="contentEvaluators" class="accordion-collapse collapse show" data-bs-parent="#evaluatorsAccordion">
                  <div class="accordion-body">
                    <table class="table table-sm">
                      <thead>
                        <tr>
                          <th>Evaluator</th>
                          <th>Purpose</th>
                          <th>Use When</th>
                        </tr>
                      </thead>
                      <tbody>
                        <tr>
                          <td><strong>LLM Judge</strong></td>
                          <td>Uses AI to evaluate response quality</td>
                          <td>Checking tone, accuracy, helpfulness, or custom criteria</td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                          <td><strong>Keyword</strong></td>
                          <td>Checks for required/forbidden keywords</td>
                          <td>Ensuring specific terms are present or absent</td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                          <td><strong>Exact Match</strong></td>
                          <td>Verifies exact text match</td>
                          <td>Testing deterministic outputs</td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                          <td><strong>Pattern Match</strong></td>
                          <td>Checks for text patterns</td>
                          <td>Validating response structure or format</td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                          <td><strong>Length</strong></td>
                          <td>Validates response length</td>
                          <td>Ensuring responses aren't too short or too long</td>
                        </tr>
                      </tbody>
                    </table>
                  </div>
                </div>
              </div>

              <!-- Format Evaluators -->
              <div class="accordion-item">
                <h2 class="accordion-header">
                  <button class="accordion-button collapsed" type="button" data-bs-toggle="collapse" data-bs-target="#formatEvaluators">
                    <i class="bi bi-file-code text-success"></i>&nbsp; Format & Structure Evaluators
                  </button>
                </h2>
                <div id="formatEvaluators" class="accordion-collapse collapse" data-bs-parent="#evaluatorsAccordion">
                  <div class="accordion-body">
                    <table class="table table-sm">
                      <thead>
                        <tr>
                          <th>Evaluator</th>
                          <th>Purpose</th>
                          <th>Use When</th>
                        </tr>
                      </thead>
                      <tbody>
                        <tr>
                          <td><strong>Format</strong></td>
                          <td>Validates JSON, Markdown, etc.</td>
                          <td>Ensuring structured output format</td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                          <td><strong>JSON Schema</strong></td>
                          <td>Validates JSON against a schema</td>
                          <td>Checking specific JSON structure and fields</td>
                        </tr>
                      </tbody>
                    </table>
                  </div>
                </div>
              </div>

              <!-- Tool Usage Evaluators -->
              <div class="accordion-item">
                <h2 class="accordion-header">
                  <button class="accordion-button collapsed" type="button" data-bs-toggle="collapse" data-bs-target="#toolEvaluators">
                    <i class="bi bi-tools text-warning"></i>&nbsp; Tool Usage Evaluators
                  </button>
                </h2>
                <div id="toolEvaluators" class="accordion-collapse collapse" data-bs-parent="#evaluatorsAccordion">
                  <div class="accordion-body">
                    <table class="table table-sm">
                      <thead>
                        <tr>
                          <th>Evaluator</th>
                          <th>Purpose</th>
                          <th>Use When</th>
                        </tr>
                      </thead>
                      <tbody>
                        <tr>
                          <td><strong>Function Call</strong></td>
                          <td>Verifies function/tool calls</td>
                          <td>Ensuring agent uses the right tools</td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                          <td><strong>Web Search</strong></td>
                          <td>Validates web search usage</td>
                          <td>Checking search queries and sources</td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                          <td><strong>Code Interpreter</strong></td>
                          <td>Validates code execution</td>
                          <td>Ensuring code runs and produces expected output</td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                          <td><strong>File Search</strong></td>
                          <td>Checks file search usage</td>
                          <td>Validating knowledge base queries</td>
                        </tr>
                      </tbody>
                    </table>
                  </div>
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>

            <div class="alert alert-info mt-3">
              <strong><i class="bi bi-lightbulb"></i> Choosing the Right Evaluators:</strong>
              <ul class="mb-0 mt-2">
                <li>Start with 1-2 evaluators that test the most critical aspects</li>
                <li>Combine evaluators for comprehensive testing (e.g., LLM Judge + Keyword)</li>
                <li>Use specific evaluators (Keyword, Format) for deterministic checks</li>
                <li>Use LLM Judge for subjective quality assessment</li>
              </ul>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- Step 4: Configuring Evaluators -->
      <section id="step4" class="mb-5">
        <div class="card">
          <div class="card-header bg-light">
            <h3 class="mb-0">Step 4: Configuring Evaluators</h3>
          </div>
          <div class="card-body">
            <p>Each evaluator has specific configuration options. Here are examples for the most common evaluators:</p>

            <h5><i class="bi bi-robot"></i> LLM Judge Evaluator</h5>
            <div class="bg-light p-3 rounded mb-3">
              <p class="mb-2"><strong>Purpose:</strong> Uses an AI model to evaluate response quality based on custom instructions.</p>
              <table class="table table-sm table-bordered mb-0">
                <tr>
                  <td><strong>Judge Model</strong></td>
                  <td>The LLM to use for evaluation (e.g., <code>gpt-4o-mini</code>, <code>claude-sonnet-4</code>)</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                  <td><strong>Custom Instructions</strong></td>
                  <td>What to evaluate (e.g., "Check if the response is empathetic and professional")</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                  <td><strong>Threshold Score</strong></td>
                  <td>Minimum score (0-100) to pass (default: 70)</td>
                </tr>
              </table>
            </div>

            <h5><i class="bi bi-search"></i> Keyword Evaluator</h5>
            <div class="bg-light p-3 rounded mb-3">
              <p class="mb-2"><strong>Purpose:</strong> Checks for presence or absence of specific keywords.</p>
              <table class="table table-sm table-bordered mb-0">
                <tr>
                  <td><strong>Required Keywords</strong></td>
                  <td>Keywords that must appear (e.g., <code>["thank you", "help"]</code>)</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                  <td><strong>Forbidden Keywords</strong></td>
                  <td>Keywords that must NOT appear (e.g., <code>["error", "failed"]</code>)</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                  <td><strong>Case Sensitive</strong></td>
                  <td>Whether matching is case-sensitive (default: false)</td>
                </tr>
              </table>
            </div>

            <h5><i class="bi bi-rulers"></i> Length Evaluator</h5>
            <div class="bg-light p-3 rounded mb-3">
              <p class="mb-2"><strong>Purpose:</strong> Validates response length is within acceptable range.</p>
              <table class="table table-sm table-bordered mb-0">
                <tr>
                  <td><strong>Min Length</strong></td>
                  <td>Minimum character count (e.g., <code>50</code>)</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                  <td><strong>Max Length</strong></td>
                  <td>Maximum character count (e.g., <code>500</code>)</td>
                </tr>
              </table>
            </div>

            <h5><i class="bi bi-tools"></i> Function Call Evaluator</h5>
            <div class="bg-light p-3 rounded mb-3">
              <p class="mb-2"><strong>Purpose:</strong> Verifies the agent called the expected functions/tools.</p>
              <table class="table table-sm table-bordered mb-0">
                <tr>
                  <td><strong>Expected Functions</strong></td>
                  <td>List of function names (e.g., <code>["search_products", "get_price"]</code>)</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                  <td><strong>Require All</strong></td>
                  <td>Whether all functions must be called (true) or just one (false)</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                  <td><strong>Check Arguments</strong></td>
                  <td>Whether to validate function arguments (default: false)</td>
                </tr>
              </table>
            </div>

            <div class="alert alert-warning">
              <strong><i class="bi bi-exclamation-triangle"></i> Important:</strong>
              Click on an evaluator card in the test form to expand its configuration options.
              Each evaluator will show a form with its specific settings.
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- Step 5: Creating Test Data (Datasets) -->
      <section id="step5" class="mb-5">
        <div class="card">
          <div class="card-header bg-light">
            <h3 class="mb-0">Step 5: Creating Test Data (Datasets)</h3>
          </div>
          <div class="card-body">
            <p>
              <strong>Datasets</strong> are collections of test data (input variables) that allow you to run
              the same test across multiple scenarios. This is essential for comprehensive testing.
            </p>

            <h5>What is a Dataset?</h5>
            <div class="row g-3 mb-4">
              <div class="col-md-6">
                <div class="card border-info h-100">
                  <div class="card-body">
                    <h6 class="card-title"><i class="bi bi-database text-info"></i> Dataset</h6>
                    <p class="card-text small mb-2">A collection of test scenarios with a consistent schema</p>
                    <p class="card-text small mb-0">
                      <strong>Example:</strong> "Customer Support Scenarios"
                    </p>
                  </div>
                </div>
              </div>
              <div class="col-md-6">
                <div class="card border-success h-100">
                  <div class="card-body">
                    <h6 class="card-title"><i class="bi bi-table text-success"></i> Dataset Rows</h6>
                    <p class="card-text small mb-2">Individual test cases with specific variable values</p>
                    <p class="card-text small mb-0">
                      <strong>Example:</strong> Row 1: <code>{ customer_name: "John", issue: "billing" }</code>
                    </p>
                  </div>
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>

            <h5>Creating a Dataset</h5>
            <div class="alert alert-primary">
              <strong><i class="bi bi-arrow-right-circle"></i> Steps:</strong>
              <ol class="mb-0 mt-2">
                <li>From the Prompt Version page, click <strong>"Datasets"</strong> button</li>
                <li>Click <strong>"+ New Dataset"</strong></li>
                <li>Enter a name and description</li>
                <li>The schema is automatically set from your prompt's variables</li>
                <li>Click <strong>"Create Dataset"</strong></li>
              </ol>
            </div>

            <h5 class="mt-4">Adding Rows Manually</h5>
            <p>Once you've created a dataset, you can add test data rows:</p>
            <ol>
              <li>Click <strong>"Add Row Manually"</strong></li>
              <li>Fill in values for each variable defined in your prompt</li>
              <li>Click <strong>"Add Row"</strong></li>
              <li>Repeat for each test scenario</li>
            </ol>

            <div class="alert alert-success">
              <strong><i class="bi bi-check-circle"></i> Pro Tip:</strong>
              Create datasets that cover:
              <ul class="mb-0 mt-2">
                <li><strong>Happy path:</strong> Normal, expected inputs</li>
                <li><strong>Edge cases:</strong> Unusual but valid inputs</li>
                <li><strong>Error cases:</strong> Invalid or problematic inputs</li>
                <li><strong>Boundary conditions:</strong> Min/max values, empty strings, etc.</li>
              </ul>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- Step 6: Generating Data with AI -->
      <section id="step6" class="mb-5">
        <div class="card">
          <div class="card-header bg-light">
            <h3 class="mb-0">Step 6: Generating Data with AI</h3>
          </div>
          <div class="card-body">
            <p>
              Instead of manually creating test data, you can use <strong>AI to generate diverse test scenarios</strong>
              automatically based on your prompt's variable schema.
            </p>

            <h5><i class="bi bi-stars"></i> How AI Generation Works</h5>
            <div class="bg-light p-3 rounded mb-3">
              <ol class="mb-0">
                <li>PromptTracker analyzes your prompt's variable schema</li>
                <li>An LLM generates realistic, diverse test data</li>
                <li>Rows are created automatically and appear in real-time</li>
                <li>You can review and edit generated rows</li>
              </ol>
            </div>

            <h5>Using AI Generation</h5>
            <div class="alert alert-primary">
              <strong><i class="bi bi-arrow-right-circle"></i> Steps:</strong>
              <ol class="mb-0 mt-2">
                <li>From the Dataset page, click <strong>"Generate with AI"</strong></li>
                <li>Specify how many rows to generate (1-100)</li>
                <li>Optionally add custom instructions (e.g., "Focus on edge cases")</li>
                <li>Select the model to use for generation</li>
                <li>Click <strong>"Generate Rows"</strong></li>
                <li>Watch as rows appear in real-time!</li>
              </ol>
            </div>

            <h5 class="mt-4">Custom Instructions Examples</h5>
            <table class="table table-bordered">
              <thead>
                <tr>
                  <th>Instruction</th>
                  <th>Result</th>
                </tr>
              </thead>
              <tbody>
                <tr>
                  <td>"Include international names and special characters"</td>
                  <td>Generates diverse, global test data</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                  <td>"Focus on edge cases and boundary conditions"</td>
                  <td>Creates unusual but valid scenarios</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                  <td>"Generate angry customer scenarios"</td>
                  <td>Creates challenging support situations</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                  <td>"Include both simple and complex queries"</td>
                  <td>Balances easy and difficult test cases</td>
                </tr>
              </tbody>
            </table>

            <div class="alert alert-info">
              <strong><i class="bi bi-lightbulb"></i> Best Practice:</strong>
              Generate 10-20 rows initially, review them for quality, then generate more if needed.
              You can always delete or edit generated rows that don't meet your needs.
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- Step 7: Running Tests -->
      <section id="step7" class="mb-5">
        <div class="card">
          <div class="card-header bg-light">
            <h3 class="mb-0">Step 7: Running Tests</h3>
          </div>
          <div class="card-body">
            <p>Once you've created a test and prepared test data, you're ready to run it!</p>

            <h5>Two Ways to Run Tests</h5>
            <div class="row g-3 mb-4">
              <div class="col-md-6">
                <div class="card border-primary h-100">
                  <div class="card-body">
                    <h6 class="card-title"><i class="bi bi-database text-primary"></i> Run with Dataset</h6>
                    <p class="card-text small">
                      Runs the test against all rows in a dataset. Best for comprehensive testing.
                    </p>
                    <p class="card-text small mb-0">
                      <strong>Use when:</strong> You want to test multiple scenarios at once
                    </p>
                  </div>
                </div>
              </div>
              <div class="col-md-6">
                <div class="card border-success h-100">
                  <div class="card-body">
                    <h6 class="card-title"><i class="bi bi-play-circle text-success"></i> Single Run with Custom Variables</h6>
                    <p class="card-text small">
                      Runs the test once with manually entered variables. Best for quick testing.
                    </p>
                    <p class="card-text small mb-0">
                      <strong>Use when:</strong> You want to test a specific scenario quickly
                    </p>
                  </div>
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>

            <h5>Running a Test with a Dataset</h5>
            <div class="alert alert-primary">
              <strong><i class="bi bi-arrow-right-circle"></i> Steps:</strong>
              <ol class="mb-0 mt-2">
                <li>From the Prompt Version page, find your test in the Tests table</li>
                <li>Click the <strong>"Run"</strong> button (play icon)</li>
                <li>Select <strong>"Run against dataset"</strong></li>
                <li>Choose a dataset from the dropdown</li>
                <li>Click <strong>"Run Test"</strong></li>
                <li>The test will run against all rows in the dataset</li>
              </ol>
            </div>

            <h5 class="mt-4">Running a Single Test</h5>
            <div class="alert alert-success">
              <strong><i class="bi bi-arrow-right-circle"></i> Steps:</strong>
              <ol class="mb-0 mt-2">
                <li>Click the <strong>"Run"</strong> button on your test</li>
                <li>Select <strong>"Single run with custom variables"</strong></li>
                <li>Enter values for each variable</li>
                <li>Click <strong>"Run Test"</strong></li>
              </ol>
            </div>

            <h5 class="mt-4">Running All Tests</h5>
            <p>You can also run all tests for a prompt version at once:</p>
            <ol>
              <li>Click the <strong>"Run All Tests"</strong> button at the top of the Tests section</li>
              <li>Choose dataset or custom variables mode</li>
              <li>All enabled tests will be queued and run</li>
            </ol>

            <div class="alert alert-info">
              <strong><i class="bi bi-clock"></i> Test Execution:</strong>
              Tests run in the background. You'll see real-time updates as they complete.
              The page will automatically refresh to show results.
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- Step 8: Analyzing Test Results -->
      <section id="step8" class="mb-5">
        <div class="card">
          <div class="card-header bg-light">
            <h3 class="mb-0">Step 8: Analyzing Test Results</h3>
          </div>
          <div class="card-body">
            <p>After running tests, you'll see detailed results for each test run.</p>

            <h5>Understanding Test Results</h5>
            <table class="table table-bordered">
              <thead>
                <tr>
                  <th>Column</th>
                  <th>What It Shows</th>
                </tr>
              </thead>
              <tbody>
                <tr>
                  <td><strong>Status</strong></td>
                  <td>
                    <span class="badge bg-success">Passed</span> All evaluators passed<br>
                    <span class="badge bg-danger">Failed</span> One or more evaluators failed<br>
                    <span class="badge bg-warning">Running</span> Test in progress
                  </td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                  <td><strong>Run Time</strong></td>
                  <td>When the test was executed</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                  <td><strong>Response Time</strong></td>
                  <td>How long the LLM took to respond (in milliseconds)</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                  <td><strong>Cost</strong></td>
                  <td>API cost for this test run (in USD)</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                  <td><strong>Rendered Prompt</strong></td>
                  <td>The actual prompt sent to the LLM (with variables filled in)</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                  <td><strong>Output Messages</strong></td>
                  <td>The LLM's response (click to view full conversation)</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                  <td><strong>Evaluations</strong></td>
                  <td>Results from each evaluator (click to see details)</td>
                </tr>
              </tbody>
            </table>

            <h5 class="mt-4">Viewing Evaluation Details</h5>
            <p>Click on an evaluation badge to see:</p>
            <ul>
              <li><strong>Score:</strong> Numeric score (0-100)</li>
              <li><strong>Feedback:</strong> Explanation of why it passed or failed</li>
              <li><strong>Metadata:</strong> Additional details about the evaluation</li>
            </ul>

            <h5 class="mt-4">Test Statistics</h5>
            <p>At the top of the Prompt Version page, you'll see overall statistics:</p>
            <ul>
              <li><strong>Total Tests:</strong> Number of tests configured</li>
              <li><strong>Passing:</strong> Number of tests currently passing</li>
              <li><strong>Failing:</strong> Number of tests currently failing</li>
              <li><strong>Pass Rate:</strong> Percentage of tests passing</li>
              <li><strong>Test Cost:</strong> Total cost of all test runs</li>
              <li><strong>Avg Response Time:</strong> Average LLM response time</li>
            </ul>

            <div class="alert alert-warning">
              <strong><i class="bi bi-exclamation-triangle"></i> Debugging Failed Tests:</strong>
              <ol class="mb-0 mt-2">
                <li>Click on the failed test run to see details</li>
                <li>Review the rendered prompt - are variables filled correctly?</li>
                <li>Check the LLM response - does it match expectations?</li>
                <li>Review evaluator feedback - what specifically failed?</li>
                <li>Adjust your prompt, evaluator config, or test data as needed</li>
                <li>Re-run the test to verify the fix</li>
              </ol>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- Step 9: Managing Tests -->
      <section id="step9" class="mb-5">
        <div class="card">
          <div class="card-header bg-light">
            <h3 class="mb-0">Step 9: Managing Tests</h3>
          </div>
          <div class="card-body">
            <h5>Editing Tests</h5>
            <p>You can modify tests at any time:</p>
            <ol>
              <li>Click the <strong>edit icon</strong> on a test row</li>
              <li>Update name, description, or evaluators</li>
              <li>Click <strong>"Update Test"</strong></li>
            </ol>

            <h5 class="mt-4">Disabling Tests</h5>
            <p>To temporarily disable a test without deleting it:</p>
            <ol>
              <li>Edit the test</li>
              <li>Uncheck the <strong>"Enable this test"</strong> checkbox</li>
              <li>Save changes</li>
            </ol>
            <p class="text-muted small">Disabled tests won't run when you click "Run All Tests".</p>

            <h5 class="mt-4">Deleting Tests</h5>
            <p>To permanently remove a test:</p>
            <ol>
              <li>Click the <strong>delete icon</strong> on a test row</li>
              <li>Confirm the deletion</li>
            </ol>
            <p class="text-muted small">⚠️ This will also delete all test run history for this test.</p>

            <h5 class="mt-4">Re-running Tests</h5>
            <p>To re-run a specific test run with the same configuration:</p>
            <ol>
              <li>Click on a test run row to expand details</li>
              <li>Click the <strong>"Re-run"</strong> button</li>
              <li>The test will run again with the same variables</li>
            </ol>

            <div class="alert alert-success">
              <strong><i class="bi bi-check-circle"></i> Pro Tip:</strong>
              Keep your test suite clean by:
              <ul class="mb-0 mt-2">
                <li>Deleting obsolete tests when requirements change</li>
                <li>Disabling flaky tests while you investigate issues</li>
                <li>Organizing tests with clear, descriptive names</li>
                <li>Running tests regularly to catch regressions early</li>
              </ul>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- Step 10: Best Practices -->
      <section id="step10" class="mb-5">
        <div class="card">
          <div class="card-header bg-light">
            <h3 class="mb-0">Step 10: Best Practices</h3>
          </div>
          <div class="card-body">
            <h5><i class="bi bi-star"></i> Test Design</h5>
            <ul>
              <li><strong>Start small:</strong> Begin with 2-3 critical tests, then expand</li>
              <li><strong>Test one thing:</strong> Each test should validate a specific behavior</li>
              <li><strong>Use descriptive names:</strong> Make it clear what each test validates</li>
              <li><strong>Cover edge cases:</strong> Don't just test the happy path</li>
              <li><strong>Keep tests independent:</strong> Tests shouldn't depend on each other</li>
            </ul>

            <h5 class="mt-4"><i class="bi bi-database"></i> Dataset Management</h5>
            <ul>
              <li><strong>Create focused datasets:</strong> Group related scenarios together</li>
              <li><strong>Use AI generation:</strong> Save time by generating diverse test data</li>
              <li><strong>Review generated data:</strong> Always check AI-generated rows for quality</li>
              <li><strong>Update datasets:</strong> Add new scenarios as you discover edge cases</li>
              <li><strong>Version datasets:</strong> Create new datasets when requirements change significantly</li>
            </ul>

            <h5 class="mt-4"><i class="bi bi-check-circle"></i> Evaluator Selection</h5>
            <ul>
              <li><strong>Combine evaluators:</strong> Use multiple evaluators for comprehensive checks</li>
              <li><strong>Use LLM Judge wisely:</strong> Great for subjective quality, but costs more</li>
              <li><strong>Prefer deterministic evaluators:</strong> Keyword, Length, Format are faster and cheaper</li>
              <li><strong>Set realistic thresholds:</strong> Don't require 100% scores unless necessary</li>
              <li><strong>Test your evaluators:</strong> Make sure they catch real issues</li>
            </ul>

            <h5 class="mt-4"><i class="bi bi-arrow-repeat"></i> Testing Workflow</h5>
            <ul>
              <li><strong>Test before deploying:</strong> Always run tests before activating a new version</li>
              <li><strong>Run tests regularly:</strong> Catch regressions early</li>
              <li><strong>Investigate failures:</strong> Don't ignore failing tests</li>
              <li><strong>Update tests with prompts:</strong> When you change a prompt, update related tests</li>
              <li><strong>Monitor costs:</strong> Keep an eye on test execution costs</li>
            </ul>

            <h5 class="mt-4"><i class="bi bi-speedometer"></i> Performance Tips</h5>
            <ul>
              <li><strong>Use faster models for testing:</strong> Consider <code>gpt-4o-mini</code> instead of <code>gpt-4o</code></li>
              <li><strong>Limit dataset size:</strong> 10-50 rows is usually sufficient</li>
              <li><strong>Run critical tests first:</strong> Prioritize tests that catch the most important issues</li>
              <li><strong>Use caching:</strong> Some evaluators cache results to save costs</li>
            </ul>

            <div class="alert alert-info">
              <strong><i class="bi bi-lightbulb"></i> Golden Rule:</strong>
              A good test suite gives you confidence to deploy changes quickly while catching real issues.
              If tests are too strict, you'll ignore failures. If they're too loose, they won't catch problems.
              Find the right balance for your use case.
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- Common Issues -->
      <section id="common-issues" class="mb-5">
        <div class="card border-warning">
          <div class="card-header bg-warning text-dark">
            <h3 class="mb-0"><i class="bi bi-exclamation-triangle"></i> Common Issues & Solutions</h3>
          </div>
          <div class="card-body">
            <div class="accordion" id="issuesAccordion">
              <!-- Issue 1 -->
              <div class="accordion-item">
                <h2 class="accordion-header">
                  <button class="accordion-button" type="button" data-bs-toggle="collapse" data-bs-target="#issue1">
                    Test fails with "Invalid Schema" error
                  </button>
                </h2>
                <div id="issue1" class="accordion-collapse collapse show" data-bs-parent="#issuesAccordion">
                  <div class="accordion-body">
                    <p><strong>Problem:</strong> Dataset schema doesn't match the prompt version's variables.</p>
                    <p><strong>Solution:</strong></p>
                    <ol class="mb-0">
                      <li>Go to the Dataset page</li>
                      <li>Check if there's an "Invalid Schema" warning</li>
                      <li>Create a new dataset with the updated schema</li>
                      <li>Copy rows from the old dataset to the new one (or regenerate with AI)</li>
                    </ol>
                  </div>
                </div>
              </div>

              <!-- Issue 2 -->
              <div class="accordion-item">
                <h2 class="accordion-header">
                  <button class="accordion-button collapsed" type="button" data-bs-toggle="collapse" data-bs-target="#issue2">
                    LLM Judge evaluator always fails
                  </button>
                </h2>
                <div id="issue2" class="accordion-collapse collapse" data-bs-parent="#issuesAccordion">
                  <div class="accordion-body">
                    <p><strong>Problem:</strong> LLM Judge is too strict or instructions are unclear.</p>
                    <p><strong>Solution:</strong></p>
                    <ol class="mb-0">
                      <li>Review the custom instructions - are they clear and specific?</li>
                      <li>Lower the threshold score (try 60-70 instead of 80-90)</li>
                      <li>Check the feedback to understand why it's failing</li>
                      <li>Refine instructions to focus on what really matters</li>
                      <li>Consider using a different judge model</li>
                    </ol>
                  </div>
                </div>
              </div>

              <!-- Issue 3 -->
              <div class="accordion-item">
                <h2 class="accordion-header">
                  <button class="accordion-button collapsed" type="button" data-bs-toggle="collapse" data-bs-target="#issue3">
                    Test runs are too expensive
                  </button>
                </h2>
                <div id="issue3" class="accordion-collapse collapse" data-bs-parent="#issuesAccordion">
                  <div class="accordion-body">
                    <p><strong>Problem:</strong> Running tests costs too much in API fees.</p>
                    <p><strong>Solution:</strong></p>
                    <ol class="mb-0">
                      <li>Use cheaper models for testing (e.g., <code>gpt-4o-mini</code> instead of <code>gpt-4o</code>)</li>
                      <li>Reduce dataset size - 10-20 rows is often enough</li>
                      <li>Use fewer LLM Judge evaluators (they're the most expensive)</li>
                      <li>Prefer deterministic evaluators (Keyword, Length, Format)</li>
                      <li>Run tests selectively instead of running all tests every time</li>
                    </ol>
                  </div>
                </div>
              </div>

              <!-- Issue 4 -->
              <div class="accordion-item">
                <h2 class="accordion-header">
                  <button class="accordion-button collapsed" type="button" data-bs-toggle="collapse" data-bs-target="#issue4">
                    Variables not being replaced in prompt
                  </button>
                </h2>
                <div id="issue4" class="accordion-collapse collapse" data-bs-parent="#issuesAccordion">
                  <div class="accordion-body">
                    <p><strong>Problem:</strong> Variables like <code>{{ customer_name }}</code> appear literally in the rendered prompt.</p>
                    <p><strong>Solution:</strong></p>
                    <ol class="mb-0">
                      <li>Check variable names match exactly (case-sensitive)</li>
                      <li>Ensure variables are defined in the prompt version's schema</li>
                      <li>Verify dataset rows have values for all required variables</li>
                      <li>Check for typos in variable names</li>
                    </ol>
                  </div>
                </div>
              </div>

              <!-- Issue 5 -->
              <div class="accordion-item">
                <h2 class="accordion-header">
                  <button class="accordion-button collapsed" type="button" data-bs-toggle="collapse" data-bs-target="#issue5">
                    Test results are inconsistent
                  </button>
                </h2>
                <div id="issue5" class="accordion-collapse collapse" data-bs-parent="#issuesAccordion">
                  <div class="accordion-body">
                    <p><strong>Problem:</strong> Same test passes sometimes and fails other times.</p>
                    <p><strong>Solution:</strong></p>
                    <ol class="mb-0">
                      <li>Lower the temperature in model settings (try 0.3 or 0.5)</li>
                      <li>Use more specific evaluators instead of relying only on LLM Judge</li>
                      <li>Make your prompt more deterministic with clear instructions</li>
                      <li>Check if the LLM is using tools inconsistently</li>
                      <li>Consider if the test expectations are too strict</li>
                    </ol>
                  </div>
                </div>
              </div>

              <!-- Issue 6 -->
              <div class="accordion-item">
                <h2 class="accordion-header">
                  <button class="accordion-button collapsed" type="button" data-bs-toggle="collapse" data-bs-target="#issue6">
                    Can't select dataset when running test
                  </button>
                </h2>
                <div id="issue6" class="accordion-collapse collapse" data-bs-parent="#issuesAccordion">
                  <div class="accordion-body">
                    <p><strong>Problem:</strong> No datasets appear in the dropdown.</p>
                    <p><strong>Solution:</strong></p>
                    <ol class="mb-0">
                      <li>Create a dataset first (click "Datasets" button from the version page)</li>
                      <li>Add at least one row to the dataset</li>
                      <li>Ensure the dataset schema matches the prompt version's variables</li>
                      <li>Refresh the page if you just created the dataset</li>
                    </ol>
                  </div>
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

